            <img src="images/icon.png" alt="Gai Jatra Icon" style="width:1.2em; height:1.2em; vertical-align:middle;">
            Gai Jatra Festival
        </h1>
        <p>A Traditional Festival of Nepal</p>
    </header>
    <main>
        <section class="About">
            <h2>About</h2>
            <p>
                Gai Jatra, the "Festival of Cows," is celebrated mainly in the Kathmandu Valley. 
                Families who lost loved ones in the past year join processions with decorated cows 
                or children dressed as cows. The festival blends remembrance with joy, humor, and culture.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>History</h2>
            <p>
                Originating in the Malla period, King Pratap Malla introduced the festival to comfort 
                his queen after the loss of their son. He encouraged families to come together, showing 
                that death is universal and part of life.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Celebration</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Processions with cows or children in cow costumes.</li>
                <li>Colorful costumes, dances, and cultural performances.</li>
                <li>Comedy, satire, and songs that freely express opinions.</li>
            </ul>

        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Gallery</h2>
            <img src="images/GAI JATRA.png" alt="Gai Jatra Image 1" width="300">
            <img src="images/gaijatra2.jpg" alt="Gai Jatra Image" width="400">
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Conclusion</h2>
            <p>
                Gai Jatra is a unique Nepali festival that celebrates life, honors the departed, 
                and spreads joy through humor and unity. 
            </p>
        </section>
